  comment          = {``While all policies appear to involve some level of design, there are at the same time degrees to which design is involved'' p19

``Jan Tinbergen (1958, 3) ... argued, design ... was an alternative to ``decisions taken on the basis of a general idea of progress and often somewhat haphazardly'' ''

Ideas of design in policy making date back to mid 20th century

``can we develop templates for interventions that can have utility beyond a narrow range of issues and a narrow range of contexts? Or should we be more concerned with specific designs for specific issues rather than assuming that we can develop generic designs?''

``a good deal of ideological thinking about policy that assumes that a simple world view can provide policy guidance ,,, tends to eschew evidence in favor of commitment, and to assume that complex policy problems can be solved through relatively simple solutions ... in marked contrast to the emphasis on “evidence” and policy learning in much of the contemporary academic literature on public policy (Pawson, 2006)''

The main point returned to several times in this chapter is that design is a conscious effort

Argues that design for policy is different to other design in that that the objects if that design - people and organisations - not not necessarily behave as expected. ``individual behavior is the ultimate target of most policy design'' p9

Bobrow 2007 lists 10 principles of policy design:
1. discipline breakout
2. minimum conditions
3. safeguards
4. placement (time)
5. oppositional analysis
6. borrowing
7. tinkering
8. backward mapping
9. forward mapping
10. judgement

``some weaknesses of designing in the public sector arise because of failure to involve the range of actors influenced by the policy'' Who to include? - problem framing is essential

``must necessarily be concerned with fundamental human values'' but decision makers too often desguising this in utility calculations which discount e.g. the future p10

Policy design involves:
- values
- conflict
- targetting and modulation

Discusses types of policy design:
- programmes (these make up policy)
- ideological design (very common)
- political design - reflects contention between alternative designs and the outcome of a political process that chooses among them
- design by transfer - defusion of ideas, especially if evidence-based
- design by innovation - what many think of as design, but is difficult in policy - tends to be more participatory because there's an assumption that participation brings a wider range of ideas
- accidental and experimental design - or policy from bottom up - or something that occurs in a crisis - although most policy is actually accidental and experimentation is often ongoing but under the radar
- non-design - ``for public policy non-decisions are decisions'' - ``while designing policy is active, important policies persist because of the absence of that activity'' p20

Model of policy design originally published in the 1980s - design requires at least four elements: 
- an understanding of causation
- an understanding of instruments available to address the problem
- an explicit understanding of the values by which the outcomes of the policy should be evaluated
- a plan for intervention

Also, an understanding of the manner in which these four elements interact p21

This model combines into policy paradigms - ideas and standards that specify the goals of policy. There is a need to be cognizent of the paradigm and challenge it so as not to repeat mistakes.

Over time there has been an increase in the number of policy problems, an increase the the instruments and tools available to address this and thus an increase in the complexity of policy problems

Critiques of policy literature:
- narrow focus
- reactive style of designing
- narrow temporal considerations
- uncertainty and risk (inadqueate attention to)
- The tabula rasa - policy is created in an existing policy landscape with policy path dependence
- context
- instrumentalism (overemphasis on instruments)},
