@Article{Renn2006,
  author           = {Ortwin Renn},
  date             = {2006},
  journaltitle     = {Land Use Policy},
  title            = {Participatory processes for designing environmental policies},
  doi              = {10.1016/j.landusepol.2004.08.005},
  pages            = {34--43},
  url              = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0264837704000882},
  volume           = {23},
  comment          = {Discusses their (with Webler) approach to bringing together (termed ``co-operative discourse''):
- technical expertise - a necessary but not a sufficient condition to make prudent environmental decisions
- public values and preferences - to legitimise decisions
- rational decision making - implication from text (p35) that this is required to address biases, anecdotal evidence and false assumptions within public perceptions

Two objectives of their model of participation: p35
1. enhance the competence in decision-making
2. assign a fair share of responsibility to those affected

Structure in discursive processes assures integration of: p40
- technical expertise
- regulatory requirements
- public values

Keywords: p34
- trust-building
- community development
- co-determination

Deliberative / participatory approach overcomes flaws of decisionistic model of communication in which expert panel informs elected representatives who then make decisions based on public values, which relies on choice of concerns and values by the representatives. Ambiguity and dissent among experts and other factors. Affected groups demand that their values and preferences are taken into account. p40-1

A common platform for mutual exchange of ideas, arguments and concerns ``danger that each group trespasses its legitimate boundary of expertise. If perceptions replace assessments and the rhetoric of powerful agents replaces value input by those who have to bear the potential impacts, the discourse goes into the wrong direction'' p41

Largely about deliberation, the participatory nature of this is implied within the text. 

Defines and discusses deliberation. p35-7

Habermas and others consider it rational if all participants are required to: p35-6
- seek consensus
- articulate and criticise factual claims on the basis of scientific and other forms of problem-adequate knowledge
- interpret factual evidence using formal logic and analytical reasoning
- disclose relevant values and preferences
- process data, arguments and evaluations in a structured format

Habermas does not address rival rationalities in terms of power, influence and significance, which matters when considering who to select to participate.

Deliberation is needed to define and role and relevance for choice making of two forms of knowledge: p36
- systematic (scientifically derived)
- ideosyncratic (derived from experience and familiarity with local conditions)

Deliberation is also needed to: p36
- find the most appropriate way to deal with uncertainty
- set efficient and fair trade-off
- address wider concerns of affected groups

Deliberation can also: p36-7
- enhance understanding
- generate new options
- decrease hostility and aggressive attitudes among the participants
- explore new problem framing
- enlighten legal policy makers
- produce competent, fair and optimised solution packages
- facilitate consensus, tolerated consensus and compromise

Suggest early on that ``early involvement of the public in deliberative processes may compromise the objective of efficient and effective policy implementation or violate the principle of fairness'' p34

Co-operative Discourse has 3 steps: p37-8
1. Identification and selection of concerns and evaluative criteria - all relevant stakeholder groups to reveal their values and criteria for judging different options and these are organised using value-tree analysis
2. The identification and measurement of impacts and consequences related to different policy options - research team operationalise and transform into indicators the evaluative criteria in the value-tree using a Delphi process
3. Conducting a discourse with randomly selected citizens as jurors and representatives of interest groups as witnesses - panels of one or several groups of randomly selected citizens conducted as seminars over three to five consecutive days or over a longer period of up to 6 months

Alternative approach to this are described in: Chess and Purcell, 1999; Chess, 2000; Rowe and Frewer, 2000).

Tools: p38-9
- Value-tree analysis - identifies and organises the values of an individual or group with respect to possible decision options
- Multi-attribute utility (MAU) analysis - elicits values, criteria, and attributes and the assignment of relative weights to the different value dimensions - the participants are forced to reflect upon their opinions and search for potential hidden motives or values that might explain discrepancy between numerical model and their holistic judgements

Case studies: p39-40
- national energy policy in Germany in 1982 identified preferences from a range of pre-defined scenarios
- regional waste management planning in Black Forest in 1984-6 arrived at unanimous decision to site incinerators in the centre of most populated town in the region as a visual reminder of the need to reduce waste (recommendation still not accepted by date of this paper)
- siting of landfills in Switzerland - panels identified criteria for decisions, evaluate the data, eliminate sites for no further considerations, and prioritise suitability of remaining sites
- sewage sludge management in US - hard to tell what conclusions are from this except need to change US political culture},
  creationdate     = {2024-03-17T11:55:24},
  keywords         = {deliberative, participatory, policy, design},
  modificationdate = {2024-03-27T15:47:42},
  owner            = {izzy_olivine},
}

@InBook{PierreP2020,
