  url              = {https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fclim.2023.1325030/full},
  volume           = {5},
  comment          = {Consider the specific example of Science Policy Interface (SPI) that sits within the UN Convention to Combat Desertification (UNCCD SPI) and how expertise can matter. Perform interviews with SPI members.

``propose an analytical framework composed mainly of two components, institutional design and boundary work dynamics, which represent the key contextual factors enabling expertise to matter. A third essential component of our framework is the ``window of opportunity'' embodying ``specific moments, modes and loci for action'' (Stirling, 2014, p. 7)'' p5

Discuss the different perspectives from different fields (International Relations, IR, and Science and Technology Studies STS) of how close expertise should be to decision making and whether expertise matters. In IR, the neorealist stream regards scientific advice as epiphenomenal and even dismiss the value of scientific advice. Haas writes about epistemic communities and the need to insulate them from political influence in order to matter. Whereas IR constructivist accounts draw attention to how the global problem of climate change was constructed [I guess: by science and policy not being separated?]. STS, with ideas such as boundary work, hybridization and coproduction, resists a separation between expert and policy.

``reject quasi-epiphenomenal, neorealist treatments of expertise ... emphasize that science-policy interfaces are crucial in promoting social learning among policymakers, which is necessary for policy formulation'' p11

``Cash et al. (2003) developed a theoretical framework based on the three pillars of credibility, relevance, and legitimacy (also known as CRELE)'' p3

``knowledge can only matter if it is widely accepted by policymakers'' p4

Dimensions of the framework developed:
- institutional design (deductively derived) - formal rules and procedures
- boundary work (deductively derived) - informal science-policy interplay
- window of opportunity (inductively derived) - that expertise can seize to influence policy-making

UNCCD is a similar, but less well known body, as IPCC and IPBES. It is ``unique in its embeddedness in a political convention'' p5-6

Gives examples of how the interaction in the SPI can help scientists learn how to communicate in ways that are useful p7

Finds that small size of UNCCD and its scientific founding are valuable - easier for more non-governmental voices to be heard. Bring in experts for specific areas as required p8

Also find that state power is counteractive - member states of the global north do not value the UNCCD, some were even manipulating its language p9

Whereas some member states in the global south were staunch supporters p10

Experienced actors with expertise were able to sieze windows of opportunity to make their voices heard p10

``political side will always be the ultimate arbiter''. Not enough attention paid to power dynamics and diverse interests p11

