  journaltitle     = {Science, Technology, \& Human Values},
  title            = {``Opening Up'' and ``Closing Down'': Power, Participation, and Pluralism in the Social Appraisal of Technology},
  url              = {https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/epdf/10.1177/0162243907311265},
  comment          = {This is dense and I suspect I've only grasped about half of it

Basically questions that participatory processes are more democratically progressive than expert analysis given the dynamics of power around the processes of information and decision-making

Compare expert analysis to participatory deliberation and find parallels in terms of normative, substantive, and instrumental imperatives, sensitivity to framing conditions, justification, strategic behaviour and power. ``Yet, either approach may be undertaken and presented in such ways as alternatively conceal and reify, or acknowledge and interrogate, these pressures, sensitivities, and susceptibilities''

- appraisal is about informing
- commitment is about forming tangible social choices in the governance of science and technology

Discusses ``closing-down'' of appraisal, by which the range of outputs (e.g. different points of view) are reduced, and ``opening-up'', by which a greater number of elements and their ambiguities are delivered

