``Given the complexity of societal challenges, the contextuality of innovations as a solution to concrete problems including local users [24,25], and the variety of location-specific institutions, it seems rather unlikely that grand challenges will be solved globally (WanzenbockF2020)'' p2

``rather than focusing on mission-oriented innovation policy initiatives, this paper centres on opportunities, challenges and bottlenecks of meaningful governance structures for local economic development. The growing body of literature reflects the high expectations attached to the idea of MIP and its underlying rationale of transformational change but lacks detailing with regard to implementation at the local level''

``MIP is best implemented at the subnational level of regions and cities'' p3

Suggests a series of vital success factors of participatory processes: p10-2
- Openness to change (of all participants) p10
- Common understanding (of objectives) p10
- Motivation (of actors, e.g. via commitment, ownership) p10-1
- Trust (transparency, communcation, etc) p11
- Avoiding parallel structures (use what is already there is possible) p11
- Space for experimentation and reflection p11
- Leadership (there are many forms and requirements, although this should be transferred to LDA at end) p11-2
- Political commitment p12
- Identification and activation of ambassadors p12

``participation is not an end in itself'' p12

Appendix B provides full details for each of a set of guidelines - e.g. questions to ask of the setting - that may be worth coming back to one day},
  creationdate     = {2024-03-30T11:57:30},
  keywords         = {policy, environment, missions, participatory, design},
