Use textiling for splitting documents automatically into topically coherent chunks

``the underlying assumption of Latent Dirichlet Allocation, [is] that a single document always addresses a number of different topics to a certain extent which is given by the Dirichlet distribution'' p40

Tag parts of speech and experiments find that nouns are best for topic modelling, with adjectives identifying how words are percieved by the respective party [framing?]. The exclude very infrequent and stop words

versions of LDA:
- Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) by Blei et al. [9]
- Labeled LDA by Ramage et al. [11] extends LDA by allowing for learning from multiply labeled documents
- LogicLDA [12] by Andrzejewski et al. is an extension of LDA that offers the possibility to include first order knowledge

Use seed words to identify topics - ``if a snippet contains a seed word for a topic, we add its topic as a label''

``The result of the topic creation is a set of multinomials over word tokens that represent the different topics in a document. According to our assumptions, these multinomials represent the position of the authors of a document with respect to the respective topic''

Test their approach by applying to coalition contracts. These are written by multiple parties but are expected to be mostly influenced by the party in control and thus this should be the result of the party position inference. It seems to have worked quite well.},
  creationdate     = {2024-04-10T12:11:44},
  keywords         = {text mining, politics, step0056, topic modelling},
  modificationdate = {2024-05-07T12:20:42},
  owner            = {izzy_olivine},
