  booktitle        = {The Oxford Handbook of International Relations},
  date             = {2009-09-02},
  title            = {Scholarship and Policy-Making: Who Speaks Truth to Whom?},
  chapter          = {36},
  doi              = {10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199219322.003.0036},
  editor           = {Christian Reus-Smit and Duncan Snidal},
  publisher        = {Oxford Academic},
  url              = {https://academic.oup.com/edited-volume/34331/chapter/291362796},
  comment          = {Makes the point (and cites others who have done so) that gap between scholarship and policy-making have gone too far

Three arguments:
1. social knowledge (which is evolutionary) needs the interaction between study and making of policy - neither can make a superior claim on it
2. both the why (scholars) and the how (policy) of social knowledge are necessary
3. both have political commitments to pursue their task which are different and complementary

Different understandings of truth:
- Objective - mainly the domain of academic world since policy world manipulates truth for political ends - but objective understanding is ambitious, self-serving and demeans policy-making
- Subjective (relative) - or intersubjective in that it is (socially) constructed by epistemic community, contingent and relative (critical or historic school, Kuhn), social context even for physical sciences, constructivist especially social science
- Evolutionary - embedded in history and unfolds as history progresses (Marx), very much in the social realm as patterns are created by individuals and society and observed as such

Continues as if the last - evolutionary - is the case - and thus both scholarship and policy-making share the quest for truth

Of scholars and policy-makers, both believe they cannot bend to the other

``The science of global warming, for example, cannot dictate policy outcomes, because all knowledge is uncertain especially when it deals with creative human beings, democracies depend on persuading majorities, and no practical system has resources to cover all risks''

``Too many scholars forget the uncertainties of their knowledge and speak too glibly about truth'' (cites and quotes from Weber)

