- Habitat restoration
- Soil carbon sequestration - changing land management
- Biochar
- Bioenergy with carbon capture and storage (BECCS) 
- Ocean fertilisation
- Building with biomass
- Enhanced terrestrial weathering
- Mineral carbonation - injecting GHG into rocks in or ex situ
- Ocean alkalinity
- Direct air capture and carbon storage (DACCS) 
- Low-carbon concrete
- other approaches are also briefly described
- approaches to removing GHGs other than CO2 are also described

Detail is given on each is provided in chapter 2, including technology readiness, scalability and engineering challenges, and social and policy factors (discussion and examples of social and policy contexts of each method)

Chapter 3 discusses cross-cutting issues: resources, storage, environment, science and technology, economics, legislation, social aspects

Figure 3 shows all these approaches - DACCS stands out as a minor player [but I would argue is what most people think of as GGR]

First recommendation is to continue and increase efforts to reduce GHG emissions

Recommendations include importing sustainable biomass

Need to (p 82) ``ensure more level incentives at the margin for GGR and to pump-prime the CCS market, overcoming `first of a kind' costs and investment hold-up problems'', options:
